Interactive chart that looks at the altitude for each species of bird over the months of the year

In [17]:
birds['month'] = pd.to_datetime(birds['date_time']).dt.month
@interact(cname1 = 'month', cname2 = 'altitude', cname3 = clist)
def scanner_by_features(cname1, cname2, cname3):
    if cname3 == 'Eric':
        sel_df = birds[birds['bird_name']=='Eric']
    elif cname3 == 'Nico':
        sel_df = birds[birds['bird_name']=='Nico']
    elif cname3 == 'Sanne':
        sel_df = birds[birds['bird_name']=='Sanne']
    else:
        sel_df = birds
    fig_1 = px.scatter(sel_df, x = cname1, y = cname2)
    fig_1.show()

Strictly looking at Migration patterns for the month of April for all birds, with size showing altitude

In [20]:
birds['month'] = pd.to_datetime(birds['date_time']).dt.month
birds['altitude'] = birds['altitude'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x < 0 else x)
by_month = birds[birds['month']==4]
fig = px.scatter_mapbox(by_month, lat="latitude", lon="longitude", color="bird_name", size="altitude",
                   size_max=15, zoom=3)
fig.show()

Conclusions

Nico birds tend to fly the lowest and divert in their migration pattern along with Eric to avoid water. Sanne birds seem to take the straightest path even if that means over water. There was no clear connection between speed and altitude. The difference in average altitude over the course of the year is different showing that Eric birds are not always the highest flying birds. Nico birds tend to gain altitude later in the year whereas Eric decreases their altitude. Looking at April specifically one can clearly see the divergent paths of each birds when approaching water. April was selected as the month of choose because it was the month where average altitude was far greater than each other month.
